<section class="section bg-cream">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header centered">
            <span class="section-eyebrow">Why Drip for Grapes</span>
            <h2>How Drip Irrigation Elevates Grape Quality</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="three-col-grid">
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🍇</div>
                <h3>Regulated Deficit Irrigation</h3>
                <p>RDI applied strategically during lag phase and veraison concentrates sugars, anthocyanins, and terpenes while controlling excessive canopy growth. Drip provides the resolution to execute RDI with vineyard-block precision.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🌿</div>
                <h3>Canopy Architecture Control</h3>
                <p>Excess water drives excessive shoot growth that shades fruit zones, increases disease pressure, and elevates labor costs. Drip's controlled delivery keeps canopy vigor in the zone agronomists target.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🦠</div>
                <h3>Reduced Powdery Mildew Pressure</h3>
                <p>Wet soil surfaces and high canopy humidity from overhead or flood irrigation create ideal conditions for powdery mildew. SDI's dry-surface delivery dramatically reduces these humidity-driven infection events.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🧪</div>
                <h3>Root-Zone Fertigation</h3>
                <p>Potassium, zinc, and boron applications via drip at critical phenological stages — bloom, set, veraison — are more effective than foliar applications and improve nutrient use efficiency by 40–60%.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🌡️</div>
                <h3>Heat Event Response</h3>
                <p>During heat dome events, SDI allows rapid soil moisture replenishment before plant stress develops. Unlike sprinklers, drip doesn't risk sunburn through water droplet lens effects during peak irradiance.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="highlight-card">
                <div class="highlight-card-icon">📊</div>
                <h3>Case Study: Paso Robles</h3>
                <p>A 320-acre Cabernet operation converted from flood to SDI, cutting water from 3.2 to 1.6 AF/acre while improving average Brix from 24.1 to 25.7 and receiving a $0.18/lb quality premium from their winery contract.</p>
                <a href="/growers-stories" class="btn-primary-sm" style="margin-top:16px;">Read More Stories →</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

